    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1945-02-07T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1945-02-07T00:00:00-05:00" n="363"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d363">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.0011 <gloss target="#t_EW1">EW</gloss>/1–2745:
                    Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Acting Secretary of State</hi> (<persName
                        corresp="#p_GJC1" type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Grew</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">top secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1945-02-07">February 7</date>
                        <date calendar="gregorian" when="1945-02-08">[<hi rend="italic">8</hi>],
                            1945.</date>
                        <note n="1" xml:id="d363fn1">The text of this message in the Defense Files
                            bears the date February 8, which is the date under which it was
                            transmitted.</note>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>War Department has just made available message dated February 7 from <persName
                        corresp="#p_M4">Marshall</persName>
                    <note n="2" xml:id="d363fn2">Not printed.</note> which indicates that <gloss
                        target="#t_JCS1">JCS</gloss> on February 7 approved with certain changes
                    British preliminary text of agreement with Soviet Union for exchange of
                    prisoners of war and apparently also for liberated persons. (This is our message
                    No. 27.)<note n="3" xml:id="d363fn3">i. e., from the Acting Secretary to the
                        Secretary since the departure of the latter from Washington, in this series
                        of messages sent via Army channels.</note> While it is not definitely clear
                    what preliminary British text is referred to, if it is the preliminary text
                    included in <gloss target="#t_JCS1">JCS</gloss> 1266,<note n="4"
                        xml:id="d363fn4">Not printed. See text agreed upon by the Combined Chiefs of
                        Staff, <hi rend="italic">post</hi>, <ref target="#pg_754">pp. 754</ref>–<ref
                            target="#pg_756">756</ref>.</note> the agreement would not appear to
                    cover the following specific points which were incorporated in the United States
                    counterproposals forwarded to <gloss target="#t_JCS1">JCS</gloss> staff with
                    you: <list>
                        <label>1.</label>
                        <item>Protection of Geneva Convention<note n="5" xml:id="d363fn5">For the
                                text of this Convention Relative to the Treatment of Prisoners of
                                War, which was signed at Geneva July 27, 1929, on the part of the
                                United States and forty-six other countries, see Department of State
                                Treaty Series No. 846, or 47 <gloss target="#t_Stat1">Stat</gloss>.
                                2021.</note> which we have informed Soviet Government we will accord
                            to Soviet citizens captured in German uniform who demand such
                            protection.</item>
                        <label>2.</label>
                        <item>Soviet citizens in the United States not prisoners of war whose cases
                            the Attorney General feels should be dealt with on basis of traditional
                            American policy of asylum.</item>
                        <label>3.</label>
                        <item>Persons liberated by United States forces no longer in their
                            custody.</item>
                        <label>4.</label>
                        <item>Question of the liberation and repatriation of other United Nations
                            citizens.</item>
                        <label>5.</label>
                        <item>Persons claimed as citizens by the Soviet authorities who were not
                            Soviet citizens prior to outbreak of war and do not now claim Soviet
                            citizenship.</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <p>(<hi rend="smallcaps">Allstate Horseshoe</hi>) It is felt that these questions
                    and others referred to in <gloss target="#t_JCS1">JCS</gloss> 1266 and 1266/1
                    should be brought to your attention in order that consideration may be given to
                    them before final agreement is reached.<note n="6" xml:id="d363fn6">For
                            <persName corresp="#p_SERJ1">Stettinius</persName>’ reply to this
                        message, dated February 9, 1945, see <hi rend="italic">post</hi>, <ref
                            target="#pg_756">pp. 756</ref>–<ref target="#pg_757">757</ref>.</note>
                </p>
            </div>
